# INSERT ALL Best Practices and Usage for SQL

The `INSERT ALL` statement allows you to insert multiple rows into one or more tables with a single SQL statement.

## Syntax
```sql
INSERT ALL
  INTO table_name (column1, column2) VALUES (value1, value2)
  INTO table_name (column1, column2) VALUES (value3, value4)
SELECT * FROM dual;


Best Practices
1. Use Appropriate Conditions
Ensure that you have the correct conditions for each INTO clause, especially when inserting from different sources.

2. Minimize Duplicates
Use conditions to prevent inserting duplicate records unless necessary, as this may help maintain data integrity.

3. Batch Inserts Wisely
Group similar inserts together in one INSERT ALL statement to reduce transaction overhead and enhance performance.

4. Avoid Long Statements
If the INSERT ALL statement becomes too lengthy, consider breaking it down into smaller batches for better readability and maintenance.

5. Test Performance
Analyze the performance of your INSERT ALL statements in various conditions to ensure efficiency.

Example
Consider a scenario where you want to insert multiple rows into a table named employees:

SQL
INSERT ALL
    INTO employees (id, name, department) VALUES (1, 'John Doe', 'Sales')
    INTO employees (id, name, department) VALUES (2, 'Jane Smith', 'Marketing')
    INTO employees (id, name, department) VALUES (3, 'Emily Johnson', 'IT')
SELECT * FROM dual;
This example effectively adds three new employees to the employees table.

Conclusion
The INSERT ALL statement can greatly improve the efficiency of your SQL data manipulation operations when used correctly. Always follow best practices to ensure optimal performance and data integrity.
